text.tspan: Dymaxion grids store spherical rasters using geodesic icosahedrons.
Each face of an icosahedron is a triangle, and it is possible to group these triangles into an numbered array of adjacent pairs:
Here are some templates for creating new graphics:
Pairing triangles in this way is useful since values within the triangle pairs can be easily represented using cartesian grids.
To show how this is done, we shear the unfolded arrangement above so that triangle pairs form a set of squares,
then overlay a cartesian grid on each square:
The cell values for each grid are interleaved into contiguous memory.
Any cell within the icosahedron is therefore indexed by:
1) the cartesian coordinates within the grid, "(x,y)", and
2) the id for the grid it occupies, "i", numbered 0 through 9 as shown, above.
Grouping triangles in this way is also useful since, for any cell, it is easy to find all neighbors of that cell.
This can be done procedurally, so that no memory need ever be consulted.
This last point is extremely important since modern computers are limited by the speed of memory consultation,
and storing a value for every cell would vastly increase the extent to which that is done.
Two cells within the same cartesian grid are obviously adjacent if exactly one of their cartiesian coordinates is sequential,
so any neighbor within the same grid can be identified by offsetting one of the cell's coordinates by ±1.
All that remains is to figure out how neighbors occur between cells of adjacent grids.
To do this, we must first understand how the cartesian grids themselves are neighbors to one another.
We note that each grid always has exactly four neighboring grids.
Two of these neighbors can be identified as having sequential ids (modulo 10).
These are neighboring "equatorial" grids whose border cuts across the equator
Neighboring cells on the border of such equatorial grids can be identified by offsetting
the appropriate coordinate for that pair of neighboring grids then applying modulo by the width of the grid, "n".
This generalizes so that any neighboring cells can be found in this way so long as they belong to equatorial grids,
including those neighbors that occupy the same grid, mentioned earlier.
That just leaves neighboring grids of nonsequential id. These are grids that both border the same pole.
For this reason we will consider two cases: one for neighbors that share the north pole ("northern grids"),
and one for neighbors that share the south pole ("southern grids").
Northern grids are characterized by an even numbered id,
and southern grids are characterized by an odd numbered id.
In either case, neighboring polar grids have ids that are offset by 2 (modulo 10).
Both cases of polar grids can be handled in a similar manner,
in that the contents of a neighboring polar grid must be rotated for alignment to occur.
The direction of rotation depends upon the pole being shared.
Among pairs of northern grids, the neighboring grids of higher id (modulo 10) are rotated counterclockwise.
Among pairs of southern grids, neighboring grids of higher id (modulo 10) are rotated clockwise.
Neighboring grids of lower id (modulo 10) are rotated in the opposite fashion.
When looking up neighbors of a cell, it is the grid of the cell itself that is rotated,
so in this case the grid that contains the cell must be rotated in the opposite fashion:
We see here a simpler way to describe this behavior:
if the neighbor falls outside the bounds of the cartesian grid into a grid that borders the same pole, then:
1) negate the coordinate that was offset from the largest cell index, then
2) swap the x and y coordinates.
The situation will occur iff the offset coordinate is outside the grid and the offset has the same sign as z.
The sign of z can be easily calculated as sign(z) = (-1)ⁱ
We have shown above how neighboring cells/vertices can be retrieved procedurally.
We will next show that, furthermore, the cell/vertex nearest to *any* point can be retrieved procedurally.
To show how this is done, we will first remind the reader that Dymaxion grids are geodesic icosahedrons.
When we say this, we mean to say that any edge on an icosahedron corresponds to a great circle segment on a dymaxion grid.
First, if any number of faces share a vertex, then the face belonging to any point within them
can be determined using only the longitude of that point when the vertex is the pole.
This is especially useful to identify the faces of polar coordinates.
Since each vertex has an antipode vertex, we can identify the face for any polar point
using a single call to atan2, provided the pole vertex is aligned with one of the 3d cartesian axes.
Moreover, if we impose that face bisectors also run along lines of longitude,
we have a performant way to narrow down any point on the grid to at most two faces:
Lastly, we need a way to identify the actual grid cell that is occupied by a point within a face.
The simplest way we have found to do this is to project the point onto a plane that's defined by the face,
then find coordinates for the point given a coordinate basis that's defined by face edges.
Second, if two faces share two vertices, denoted u and w,
then there exists a plane that partitions the two faces.
The normal for this plane is the cross product of the two vertices, u×w,
therefore if we know that a point occupies one of two faces,
then we can determine which of those faces is occupied
depending on the sign of the dot with the plane normal, sign(v⋅(u×w)):
This can be done to identify which of the two faces from the previous step is occupied,
however it can also be used to determine whether a point occupies a polar or equatorial face:
To convert back from grid coordinates to cartesian coordinates, we simply apply the inverse transformation and normalize.
